# Renaming columns for consistency
global_df = global_df.rename(columns={
    "Entity": "Entity",
    "Year": "Year",
    "Freshwater use": "Global_Use_BCM" # primary column
})
# Dropping duplicate unnecessary column
if "Freshwater use.1" in global_df.columns:
    global_df = global_df.drop(columns=["Freshwater use.1"])

country_df = country_df.rename(columns={
    "Entity": "Country",
    "Code": "ISO3",
    "Year": "Year",
    "Annual freshwater withdrawals, total (billion cubic meters)": "Withdrawal_BCM"
})

# dropping "time" column (not needed)
if "time" in country_df.columns:
    country_df = country_df.drop(columns=["time"])


# Removing missing values
country_df = country_df.dropna(subset=["Withdrawal_BCM"])

# Counting countries reporting per year
reporting = (
    country_df.groupby("Year")["Country"]
    .count()
    .reset_index()
    .rename(columns={"Country": "Num_Countries_Reporting"})
)

water_blue = "#0077b6"
water_blue_light = "#90e0ef"
water_blue_dark = "#023e8a"
# defining color theme

PLOT 1-Interactive Global Trend Line (Required: Interactive Plot)

In[134]:
# Ensure Year is int, not float
df = global_df.copy()
df["Year"] = df["Year"].astype(int)

# Slider binding
year_slider = alt.binding_range(
    min=df["Year"].min(),
    max=df["Year"].max(),
    step=1,
    name="Year:"
)

# Altair v5 selection_point (single value)
select_year = alt.selection_point(
    fields=["Year"],
    bind=year_slider,
    value=[{"Year": df["Year"].min()}]   # MUST be a list of dicts
)

# Base area chart
area = (
    alt.Chart(df)
    .mark_area(
        color=water_blue_light,
        opacity=0.6,
        line={"color": water_blue_dark, "strokeWidth": 2.5}
    )
    .encode(
        x=alt.X(
            "Year:O",
            title="Year",
            axis=alt.Axis(values=list(range(1900, 2020, 10)))
        ),
        y=alt.Y(
            "Global_Use_BCM:Q",
            title="Global freshwater use (trillion m)"
        )
    )
)

# Highlighted red point on selected year
point = (
    alt.Chart(df)
    .mark_circle(size=150, color="red")
    .encode(
        x="Year:O",
        y="Global_Use_BCM:Q"
    )
    .transform_filter(select_year)
)

# Combine
final_chart = (
    (area + point)
    .add_params(select_year)
    .properties(
        width=900,
        height=450,
        title="Global Freshwater Use Over the Long Run (19012014)"
    )
)

final_chart

Its fascinating how the data shows a steady increase over the decades, with a more pronounced spike starting in the mid-20th century. It's almost like a turning point that reflects humanity's efforts to feed a growing population. However, as we approached the early 2000s, the curve began to flatten somewhat, yet it still indicates that we are using more freshwater than ever before.

What stands out to us is the implication of this trend: while weve made strides in water usage efficiency, the overall levels remain concerningly high. It suggests that our freshwater resources are under increasing strain, and we need to be mindful of the growing risk of water scarcity as we move forward. This insight emphasizes the importance of sustainable water management practices to ensure we can meet future needs without compromising these vital resources.

In[135]:
# Keep only valid ISO3 rows
country_only = country_df[country_df["ISO3"].str.len() == 3].copy()

# Convert Year to integer (IMPORTANT)
country_only["Year"] = country_only["Year"].astype(int)

# Identify top 4 countries by maximum withdrawal
top4_countries = (
    country_only.groupby("Country")["Withdrawal_BCM"]
    .max()
    .sort_values(ascending=False)
    .head(4)
    .index
)

facet_plot = (
    alt.Chart(country_only[country_only["Country"].isin(top4_countries)])
    .mark_line(strokeWidth=2, color=water_blue_dark, interpolate="monotone")
    .encode(
        x=alt.X(
            "Year:Q",
            title="Year",
            axis=alt.Axis(
                values=list(range(1970, 2026, 10)),  # show ticks every decade (cleaner)
                format="d",
                labelAngle=0
            )
        ),
        y=alt.Y("Withdrawal_BCM:Q", title="Withdrawals (BCM)"),
        tooltip=[
            alt.Tooltip("Country:N", title="Country"),
            alt.Tooltip("Year:Q", title="Year", format="d"),
            alt.Tooltip("Withdrawal_BCM:Q", 
                        title="Withdrawals (billion m)", 
                        format=",")  # comma formatting
        ],
        
        facet=alt.Facet("Country:N", columns=2)
    )
    .properties(
        title="Annual Freshwater Withdrawals for Top 4 Countries (19702021)",
        width=350,
        height=250
    )
)

Pakistan's trend was also interesting; while its been steadily increasing, the recent sharp spike in its water withdrawal raised our eyebrows. It might be due to either unusual reporting practices or perhaps some changes in measurement techniques that we need to dig deeper into.

On the other hand, the United States displayed a declining trend in water usage starting from the 1980s. This decline can be attributed to improvements in water efficiency, regulatory policies, and a transition away from industries that require a lot of water.

Overall, these plots really emphasize how different factors like national policies, levels of development, and agricultural dependencies contribute to the diverse patterns of freshwater usage across these countries. Its fascinating to see how each nations approach shapes their water resources!

PLOT 3- Compound Visualization (Histogram + Density Curve)

In[136]:
# Filtering out any zeroes (log scale cannot take zero)
subset = country_df[country_df["Withdrawal_BCM"] > 0].copy()

# Adding log10 transformed column
subset["Withdrawal_log10"] = np.log10(subset["Withdrawal_BCM"])

# Histogram on log scale
hist = (
    alt.Chart(subset)
    .mark_bar(color=water_blue_dark)
    .encode(
        x=alt.X("Withdrawal_log10:Q",
                bin=alt.Bin(maxbins=40),
                title="Log10(Water Withdrawals BCM)"),
        y=alt.Y("count():Q", title="Number of Countries"),
        tooltip=["count()"]
    )
    .properties(width=350, height=300)
)

# Density curve (log scale)
density = (
    alt.Chart(subset)
    .transform_density(
        "Withdrawal_log10",
        as_=["Withdrawal_log10", "density"]
    )
    .mark_line(color="crimson", strokeWidth=3)
    .encode(
        x=alt.X("Withdrawal_log10:Q",
                title="Log10(Water Withdrawals BCM)"),
        y=alt.Y("density:Q", title="Density")
    )
    .properties(width=350, height=300)
)

compound = (hist | density).properties(
    title="Distribution of Freshwater Withdrawals Across Countries (Log Scale)"
)

compound
Out[136]:

As a team, we took a closer look at the histogram and density curve representing freshwater withdrawals across different countries, and what we found was quite revealing. Its clear that theres a significant skew in the data. Most nations are withdrawing relatively modest amounts of freshwater, typically between log10 values of 8.5 and 9.5. In practical terms, that means the majority of countries are using somewhere between 300 million and 3 billion cubic meters per year.

However, we also noticed that only a handful of countries are outliers on the far right of the distribution, where massive consumers like India, China, and the U.S. stand out. This stark contrast really drives home the point about global inequality in water consumption, just a few nations are responsible for the lion's share of total withdrawals.

We agreed that using a log scale here is crucial since the volume of withdrawals spans several orders of magnitude. It helps us visualize the disparities in a way thats much clearer. Overall, our discussions highlighted the need to address these imbalances in water usage on a global scale.

PLOT 4 Choropleth Map (Required: Geospatial Plot)

In[140]:
# Determine latest year
latest_year = country_df["Year"].max()
latest = country_df[country_df["Year"] == latest_year].copy()

# Create readable "Billions" column
latest["Withdrawal_BCM_Billions"] = latest["Withdrawal_BCM"] / 1e9

# Clean names for matching
latest["Country_clean"] = latest["Country"].str.strip()

# FIXing NAME MISMATCHES FOR MERGING
name_fixes = {
    "United States": "United States of America",   # needed
    "Democratic Republic of Congo": "Democratic Republic of Congo",
    "Congo": "Republic of the Congo",
    "Congo, Dem. Rep.": "Democratic Republic of the Congo",
    "Eswatini": "Swaziland",
    "Cte d'Ivoire": "Ivory Coast",
    "Cape Verde": "Cabo Verde",
    "Micronesia": "Federated States of Micronesia",
    "So Tom and Prncipe": "Sao Tome and Principe",
    "Czechia": "Czechia",
    "Myanmar": "Myanmar",
    "Russia": "Russia",
    "South Korea": "South Korea",
    "North Korea": "North Korea",
    "Vietnam": "Vietnam",
    "Syria": "Syria",
    "Iran": "Iran",
    "Tanzania": "Tanzania"
}


latest["Country_clean"] = latest["Country_clean"].replace(name_fixes)

# Loading world map
world = alt.topo_feature(
    "https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/world-atlas@2/countries-110m.json",
    "countries"
)

# Building choropleth
choropleth = (
    alt.Chart(world)
    .mark_geoshape(stroke="white", strokeWidth=0.5)
    .transform_lookup(
        lookup="properties.name",
        from_=alt.LookupData(
            latest,
            key="Country_clean",
            fields=["Country", "Withdrawal_BCM", "Withdrawal_BCM_Billions", "Year"]
        )
    )
    .encode(
        color=alt.Color(
            "Withdrawal_BCM:Q",
            title="Withdrawals (BCM)",
            scale=alt.Scale(scheme="blues")
        ),
        tooltip=[
            alt.Tooltip("Country:N", title="Country"),
            alt.Tooltip("Withdrawal_BCM_Billions:Q",
                        title="Withdrawals (Billion m)",
                        format=",.1f"),
            alt.Tooltip("Withdrawal_BCM:Q",
                        title="Withdrawals (m)",
                        format=",.0f"),
            alt.Tooltip("Year:Q", title="Year")
        ]
    )
    .project("naturalEarth1")
    .properties(
        title=f"Global Freshwater Withdrawals by Country ({latest_year})",
        width=900,
        height=450
    )
)

# Improved Styling + Tooltip for Plot 5  Trend in Countries Reporting

base = alt.Chart(reporting).encode(
    x=alt.X(
        "Year:Q",
        title="Year",
        axis=alt.Axis(
            values=list(range(1960, 2026, 5)),
            labelAngle=0,
            grid=False
        )
    ),
    y=alt.Y(
        "Num_Countries_Reporting:Q",
        title="Countries Reporting",
        axis=alt.Axis(grid=True, gridOpacity=0.2)
    ),
    tooltip=[
        alt.Tooltip("Year:Q", title="Year"),
        alt.Tooltip("Num_Countries_Reporting:Q", title="Countries Reporting")
    ]
)

# Background area shading
background = (
    base.mark_area(
        opacity=0.15,
        color=water_blue_dark
    )
)

# Line
line = (
    base.mark_line(
        color=water_blue_dark,
        strokeWidth=3
    )
)

# Points
points = (
    base.mark_circle(
        size=70,
        color=water_blue_dark,
        opacity=1
    )
)

# Combining layers
final_plot5 = (
    background + line + points
).properties(
    title="Trend in Countries Reporting Freshwater Withdrawal Data (19622021)",
    width=850,
    height=400
)

Research Question

1. How has global freshwater use changed from 19012014?

  • Over the years, our use of freshwater has seen some significant changes. If we look back from 1901 to 2014, its clear that weve dramatically ramped up our consumption of this vital resource.
  • From 1901 to around 1950, the increase was gradual but steady. It wasn't until after 1950 that we really started to see a sharp rise in freshwater withdrawals. This surge was largely fueled by industrialization, a booming population, and the expansion of irrigated agriculture to feed everyone.
  • The most remarkable growth happened between 1950 and 1990, a time marked by the Green Revolution and rapid economic development, especially in Asia. It was during these decades that our demand for freshwater really skyrocketed.
  • However, post-1990, the growth trend started to level off, indicating that in some areas, we might have hit a point where were using water more efficiently or have stabilized our consumption levels.
  • In summary, since the early 20th century, global freshwater use has increased more than fivefold, with the fastest growth occurring after the mid-20th century.

2. Which decades had the fastest or slowest growth in freshwater use?

  • When we look at global water usage trends, it's clear that the fastest growth occurred between the 1950s and the 1980s. During this time, we saw a significant increase in water use, driven largely by agricultural expansion, the mechanization of farming, increased fertilizer use, and overall industrial development. Countries like China and India became major players in water consumption as their economies grew.
  • In contrast, the period from the early 1900s to the 1940s experienced much slower growth. During these decades, industrial and agricultural activities were on a smaller scale, and the systems for managing global water use were not as advanced.
  • More recently, between 2000 and 2014, growth in water usage began to plateau. This slowdown is largely due to improved water-use efficiency and stricter policy regulations, as well as the saturation of demand in agricultural water use.
  • In summary, the decades from 1950 to 1980 saw the most rapid growth in water consumption, while the early 1900s and the period after 2000 had much slower increases in usage.

3. Which countries use the most freshwater, and how does this vary by year?

  • When looking at freshwater usage globally, a few countries stand out prominently. India leads the pack with the highest overall withdrawals, followed closely by China, which has seen its water usage grow rapidly. The United States comes next; although its water withdrawals are high, they have stabilized since around the 1980s, thanks to various efficiency improvements. Pakistan has significant agricultural water demands, while Brazil, Indonesia, and Bangladesh fluctuate in their rankings depending on the year.
  • If we consider changes over time, both India and China demonstrate strong, long-term growth in water usage. In contrast, the United States peaked in the 1980s and has since seen a decline in usage. Pakistan, on the other hand, has shown steady growth in its water demands. Most countries in Africa and Europe maintain low to moderate levels of freshwater withdrawals.
  • In conclusion, while India, China, and the United States are the dominant players in global freshwater use, their patterns and trends in water consumption reveal interesting differences over time.

4. How do top water-using countries compare over time?

  • When we look at the faceted time-series plots of water consumption across different countries, several distinct trends emerge that help answer the question of how water usage varies globally.
  • Starting with India, we see a steep and consistent increase in water consumption over the past 60 years. By 2021, India had become the largest consumer of water, a trend that reflects its reliance on intensive agriculture and significant groundwater resources.
  • In China, water consumption began to experience major growth in the 1970s, coinciding with its rapid industrial boom. However, in recent years, this growth has started to stabilize, suggesting a shift in demand patterns.
  • Turning to the United States, the picture is somewhat different. Here, we saw high levels of water withdrawals between 1960 and 1980. After that period, due to regulations, the adoption of more efficient irrigation methods, and shifts in industrial practices, water withdrawals have declined significantly.
  • Finally, in Pakistan, there's been a steady upward trend in water consumption, largely driven by agriculture that relies heavily on water resources.
  • In conclusion, it's clear that different countries exhibit distinct patterns in water usage. Rapidly growing economies like India and China tend to see quick increases, whereas developed nations like the United States tend to stabilize or even decrease their consumption over time.

5. How does the global distribution of freshwater withdrawals change over time?

  • When we take a closer look at the histogram and the density on a log scale, along with the choropleth map, we can see some interesting patterns regarding water usage across different countries.
  • Firstly, its clear that the distribution of water usage is quite skewed. Most countries are in the lower range, using very little watertypically between 10 and 10 cubic meters per year. However, there's a small group of countries that stand out because they consume enormous amounts, with figures reaching into the 10 to 10 cubic meters per year. This significant inequality in water withdrawal volumes has remained consistent over time.
  • Geographically, Asia really stands out as the leader in high water withdrawals, particularly countries like India, China, and Pakistan. North America also plays a crucial role, mainly due to the massive consumption by the U.S. On the other hand, Africa shows a different trend with generally low water usage, but there is a noticeable increase in participation over the years. Europe, meanwhile, tends to maintain moderate and stable levels of water use.
  • It's also worth noting the trend in reporting. Back in the 1960s, only a handful of countries reported their water usage data, but now nearly all UN nations are involved. This increase in reporting has significantly improved our understanding of global water distribution patterns in the last few decades.
  • In conclusion, while global water distribution has always been skewedwith just a few countries using the majority of the world's freshwaterwe're now in a much better position to analyze and understand these patterns thanks to improved data coverage.
